				content:
					'Fire in Tunnels: A Primer On Fire Safety Down Below  Tunnels present unique considerations in terms of fire safety, particularly due to the confined spaces and restrictive ventilation. Being involved in the design of the electrical life safety systems in Tunnels for the last 20 years from an electrical code compliance and fire resistive cabling systems aspect. Fire in a tunnel can quickly become a life threatening situation, as the smoke and heat can quickly fill the cavity, making it difficult for people to egress to safety.  Tunnel Fires In The Know  Tunnel fires are known to generate intense heat, smoke, and toxic gases, which travels rapidly throughout the tunnel and can affect large masses of people, whether a Subway, Rail or Road tunnel. The “front and center” factors that add to the threat level of a tunnel fire are inclusive of the type and quantity of combustible materials in the tunnel, the ventilation system functionality, and the geometry of the tunnel (length, round, square, dual, etc).  According to a study by N. Hua, and others in 2020 [4], the temperature of a fire in a tunnel can exceed 1000 °C (1832 F), which is hot enough to cause significant damage to the tunnel structure, and it’s infrastructure, and generate toxic gases (types and concentration depending on materials). The ventilation system can play a very critical role in controlling the spread of both heat and smoke, but it can as a result in the spread of the fire if the airflow is not managed properly.  Designing fire-resistive tunnels requires a multidisciplinary approach, involving professionals in Civil, Structural, Fire, HVAC and Electrical Engineering. First and foremost, the tunnel structure has to beable to resist the thermal temperature rise stress and continuity of heat without fear of collapse.  According to Cafaro and Bertola (2019)[1], the historic design approach for fire-resistive tunnels has been to utilizing passive fire protection, such as fire-resistant, or fire proof materials (panels, et..) and coatings, to help the tunnel structure resist the heat. This approach no matter how functional may not protect tunnel users from the toxic smoke and gases generated.  Engineers and Designers are now reviewing and utilizing active fire protection processes, such as smoke control systems, to reduce limit the smoke and toxic gases in the tunnel and support visibility for tunnel egress by civilians, and firefighting location accuracy by fire professionals. A study by Junmei Li, and others in 2021 [9] noted that smoke control systems have shown to limit the spread of smoke and heat in a tunnel during a fire condition, however, how well they work depends on the geometry of the tunnel and the scale of the ventilation system.  “How To” For Risk Control of Fires in Tunnels  The strategies that engineers can employ to reduce risk of fires in tunnels, and meanwhile protection human life, in the event of a fire.  1) Reduce the amount of combustible materials in the design or retrofit, by using non-combustible materials in the tunnel lining system, and avoid flammable liquids and gases in the tunnel when possible [10] [11]  2) Upgrade, or redesign, the ventilation to reduce the risk of fire by slowing down the spread of smoke and heat. Per NFPA 130 and NFPA 502 standards [13], tunnels should have a strong designed ventilation system, that meets or exceeds the standards, that can control smoke and heat in the event of a fire. Active ventilation systems include fans and air ducts, which can be used to control the airflow and reduce the spread of smoke and heat..  3) The ventilation system should be designed to create a negative pressure zone that prevents smoke and gases from moving to other sections of the tunnel, and still providing fresh air to people who are attempting an egress path from the tunnel. Depending on the design, natural ventilation could be used to create this negative pressure, however in larger tunnels mechanical ventilation systems is the only way to achieve this effect.  In the Runehamar tunnel fire tests [11] ventilation system plays a big role in mitigating the negative results of tunnel fires. Good ventilation design and operation procedures, help make the point that the design of ventilation systems should consider the geometry and operation of the tunnel, fire scenarios, and the movement of people and vehicles.  Most tunnel designers know that there is a potential for smoke to accumulate in low areas of the tunnel, known as stratification (ie.. a layer of warm air collects at tunnel ceiling level. As the smoke from a fire rises, it reaches this thermal block and lacks the energy to rise further. The smoke then builds up below the level of the of the block, creating a smoke plateau.) This can make it difficult for people to egress and can also accelerate the spread of fire. Smoke extraction fans can be installed to extricate the smoke from these low areas and prevent the stratification.  Proper emergency lighting can save the day. In the event of a power outage, emergency lighting can help guide people either out of the tunnel or to a place of shelter. As per NFPA 502, emergency lighting should be installed “at intervals not greater than 30 ft (9.1 m) along all means of egress.” The lighting should be designed to provide adequate illumination for at least 1.5 hours after a power outage.[14]  Fires in tunnels are extremely dangerous, and pose significant challenges for first responders, tunnel operators, and people stuck in the tunnel. The situational conditions of a fire depend on numerous factors, including the types of materials in the tunnel, the ventilation network, and the integrity and design of the tunnel’s fire protection systems.  Recent tunnel designs and construction processes can improve tunnel safety, maximize and speed-up evacuation procedures, and mitigate the risk of tunnel fires. Maintenance of tunnel fire protection systems must be handled on a regimented schedule for the protection of everyone.  Teamwork between stakeholders, government, and fire agency researchers is important in promoting tunnel safety and reducing tunnel fires and the risks of fatalities and injury. • “Fires in Tunnels: Learning from Disasters” by Emilio Cafaro Dipartimento di Energetica, Politecnico di Torino Volfango Bertola School of Engineering, University of Edinburgh: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259800966_Fires_in_Tunnels_Learning_from_Disasters • “Characterizing damage in a concrete lining during a tunnel fire” by Hua, N., Tessari, A., Elhami Khorasani, N. published in the journal Tunnelling and Underground Space Technology in 2021: https://engineering.buffalo.edu/civil-structural-environmental/research/research-news-highlights.host.html/content/shared/engineering/civil-structural-environmental/research/research-highlights/tunnel-fire-project.detail.html • “A review of tunnel fire damage assessment methods and techniques” by Hua, N., Tessari, A., Elhami Khorasani, N. published in the Transportation Research Record in 2021: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0361198120987228 • “Quantifying uncertainties in the temperature-time evolution of railway tunnel fires” by Hua, N., Tessari, A., Elhami Khorasani, N. published in the journal Fire Technology in 2020: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10694-020-01007-8 • “Tunnel Fire Damage Assessment: A Review” by Hua, N., Tessari, A., Elhami Khorasani, N. presented at the 100th Transportation Research Board Annual Meeting in 2021:https://trid.trb.org/view/1759383 • “Damage assessment framework for tunnel structures under fire” by Hua, N., Tessari, A., Elhami Khorasani, N. presented at the 11th International Conference on Structures in Fire in 2020: https://engineering.buffalo.edu/civil-structural-environmental/research/geomechanics-geotechnical-and-geoenvironmental-engineering.host.html/content/shared/engineering/civil-structural-environmental/research/research-highlights/tunnel-fire-project.detail.html • “Design fire scenarios for railway tunnel fires” by Hua, N., Tessari, A., Elhami Khorasani, N. presented at the IABSE Congress in 2019: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/335662563_Design_Fire_Scenarios_for_Railway_Tunnel_Fires • “Enhancing the resilience of tunnels subject to fire events” presented at the AASHTO Committee on Bridges and Structures Annual Meeting in 2021: https://www.tunnel-online.info/en/artikel/tunnel_Fire_Protection_for_new_and_existing_Underground_Structures-329612.html • “Numerical evaluation on the smoke control strategies and parameters for the road tunnel with converging junctions” by Junmei Li, Qiwei Dong, Yanfeng Li, and Zehang Wang, published in the journal Tunnelling and Underground Space Technology in 2021: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877705817349226 • Experimental Study on the Effectiveness of Mechanical Smoke Exhaust in a Long Tunnel under Fire Conditions. Fire Technology, 56(6), 2345–2366. doi: 10.1007/s10694–020–01023–5 https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10694-020-01023-5 • NFPA 502: Standard for Road Tunnels, Bridges, and Other Limited Access Highways',
